>>34161042
On the monkeys? Probably. On most other species? Probably not.
Considering that humans are a species that was fairly polygynous, I don't think it unreasonable that other species with similar mating practices (i.e. lions) would likely develop along the same lines that humans have. Monogamy is actually something that has come about largely due in part to the technological and societal advancement of humanity, and some even go as far as to say that monogamy is the reason humanity advanced. Monogamy has also been proven to be one of the greatest indicators of the overall health and success of a society, so while they likely would keep plenty of the things that we see as separating their sexual behaviors from ours, it's also quite possible that they simply either wouldn't advance with humans or would advance almost completely dependent on human advancement paving the way first. One thing that's good to remember is that primates are one of the most promiscuous groups of the entire animal kingdom, yet humans came to be one of the least; a quite clear indicator on just how much monogamy and chastity correlates with advancement, regardless of which causes the other. While many parts of our society are influenced to varying degrees by our physiology and evolutionary behaviors, the most clear and notable things are often the result of conscious decisions (how marriage is viewed very differently in different parts of the world rather than having one mostly cohesive view throughout humanity). It's likely that animals that are polygamous would end up being split between groups that view polygamy as the traditional and proper way they're supposed to function contrasted against those who viewed it as backwards and holding them behind (again, much the same way that humans do).
You probably wouldn't have to physically fight off would-be suitors much more than you do in human society.
